<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1904-10-14T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1904-10-14T00:00:00-05:00" n="709" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d709">
                        <head><hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Hay</persName> to Mr.
                                    <persName type="to">Eddy</persName>.</hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1904-10-14"><hi rend="italic">October 14,
                                1904</hi></date>.</dateline>
                            <seg rendition="#left">No. 156.]</seg></opener>
                        <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I inclose herewith a copy of a note from
                            the Japanese minister at this capital conveying the thanks of his
                            Government to Mr. McCormick for his good offices in bringing about the
                            return to Japan of some 800 Japanese subjects, who have, until lately,
                            been remaining in Russia, and who are to leave Bremen for home about the
                            20th instant.</p>
                        <p>I am, etc.,</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">John Hay.</hi></signed></closer>
                        <postscript>
                            <p>(Note.—See No. 75, October 11, 1904, from the Japanese Legation, <ref target="#pg_436">p. 436</ref>.)</p>
                        </postscript>
                    </div>
                </body></text></TEI>